hat bore the brunt of Katrina. The findings underscore the frequently disproportionate suffering of African Americans and the agonizingly slow pace of recovery. Highlighting the lessons learned, the book offers suggestions for improved governmental emergency management techniques to increase preparedness, better mitigate storm damage, and reduce the level of trauma in future disasters. Multiple major hurricanes have unleashed their destruction in the years since Katrina, making this a crucial study whose importance only continues to grow.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aDisaster reliefxSocial aspects. 0aDisaster victimsxMental health. 0aDisaster victimsxResearchzLouisiana. 0aDisaster victimsxResearchzMississippi. 0aDisastersxPsychological aspects. 0aDisastersxSocial aspects. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aNicholls, Keith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31972740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477319741423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477319741/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK